usiness that are not directly attributed to specific business activities and can be fixed or variable. Understanding how to calculate the transfer price per unit is essential for setting prices that reflect the true cost of production and ensure goal-congruent behavior by both the selling and receiving divisions [Data: Concepts (1560, 1559); Relationships (1472, 1471)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Quizzes on transfer pricing objectives and policies test understanding of goal-congruent pricing.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The chapter includes quizzes that test the understanding of the bases for setting a transfer price that results in goal-congruent behavior by both the selling and receiving divisions. One quiz involves calculating the minimum transfer price that Division A would accept for transferring Product S to Division B, considering external demand and opportunity costs. Another quiz evaluates the objectives of a good transfer pricing system and whether a given transfer pricing policy achieves those objectives. These quizzes are designed to reinforce the theoretical concepts discussed in the chapter and provide practical applications [Data: Concepts (1562, 1561, 1563); Relationships (1474, 1473, 1475)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Transfer pricing is crucial for internal transactions and financial management.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Transfer pricing is a critical concept for managing internal transactions between different divisions of a company. The case on Implementation and Evaluation of EPOS and ERPS in XYZ Stores may involve considerations of transfer pricing for internal transactions between stores. By understanding and applying transfer pricing principles, companies can ensure that internal transactions are priced fairly and reflect the true cost of production, leading to better financial management and goal congruence across divisions [Data: Relationships (1476)].\"\n        },\n      